Below is the **complete institutional memory and performance governance architecture** for:

# üî∑ LOGIC 15 ‚Äì Supplier Performance Tracking & Memory Logic

This logic ensures that supplier participation in the procurement ecosystem is **continuously evaluated**, recorded, and factored into future sourcing decisions.

It converts one-time contracts into **long-term accountability cycles**.

---

# 1Ô∏è‚É£ PURPOSE OF LOGIC 15

This logic ensures:

* Supplier trust is performance-based
* Poor performance has consequences
* High performance is rewarded
* Institutional knowledge is retained
* Future procurement decisions are data-driven

It prevents:

* Repeated contracting with unreliable suppliers
* Loss of institutional memory due to staff turnover
* Over-reliance on price alone
* Informal or biased supplier preference

---

# 2Ô∏è‚É£ POSITION IN PROCUREMENT LIFECYCLE

This logic activates during:

```
Contract Execution (Post Logic 10)
        ‚Üì
Delivery Monitoring
        ‚Üì
Milestone Evaluation
        ‚Üì
Performance Scoring
        ‚Üì
Supplier Profile Update
        ‚Üì
Future Procurement Matching (Logic 5)
        ‚Üì
Evaluation Scoring Weight (Logic 8)
```

It closes the procurement feedback loop.

---

# 3Ô∏è‚É£ CORE PERFORMANCE DIMENSIONS

Supplier evaluation covers:

| Dimension                      | Measurement Examples                |
| ------------------------------ | ----------------------------------- |
| Timeliness                     | On-time delivery %, delay frequency |
| Quality                        | Defect rate, rework incidents       |
| Compliance                     | Adherence to contract terms         |
| Responsiveness                 | Communication speed                 |
| Financial reliability          | Payment disputes, insolvency risk   |
| Ethical conduct                | Misrepresentation, collusion flags  |
| Safety & regulatory compliance | Incident reports                    |
| Dispute history                | Arbitration or litigation cases     |

Each dimension weighted per procurement category.

---

# 4Ô∏è‚É£ PERFORMANCE DATA COLLECTION POINTS

Data captured at:

* Delivery milestone completion
* Inspection reports
* Service-level agreement (SLA) tracking
* Contract close-out review
* Payment approval stage
* Dispute resolution process

Data sources:

* Contract manager input
* Quality assurance reports
* Automated SLA tracking
* Audit findings
* Supplier self-assessment (optional)

---

# 5Ô∏è‚É£ PERFORMANCE SCORING MODEL

---

## üîπ A. Contract-Level Score

At completion:

```
Final Contract Performance Score =
(Timeliness √ó Weight)
+ (Quality √ó Weight)
+ (Compliance √ó Weight)
+ (Responsiveness √ó Weight)
+ (Risk Adjustments)
```

Scale example: 0‚Äì100.

---

## üîπ B. Rolling Supplier Score

System calculates:

```
Cumulative Supplier Score =
Weighted Average of Last N Contracts
```

More recent contracts can carry higher weight.

---

# 6Ô∏è‚É£ RISK-ADJUSTED PERFORMANCE INDEX

Performance score adjusted for:

* Contract complexity
* Emergency procurement context
* Force majeure events
* Scope changes

Prevents unfair penalization.

---

# 7Ô∏è‚É£ PERFORMANCE MEMORY STRUCTURE

Supplier profile stores:

* Overall performance rating
* Category-specific performance rating
* On-time delivery percentage
* Average quality score
* Dispute frequency ratio
* Termination incidents
* Blacklist warnings
* Risk flags history

This becomes institutional memory.

---

# 8Ô∏è‚É£ CATEGORY-SPECIFIC PERFORMANCE TRACKING

Performance segmented by:

* Construction
* IT services
* Consulting
* Equipment supply
* Maintenance contracts

A supplier strong in IT may not score high in construction.

Prevents overgeneralization.

